Selecting the best performing models and deploying them¶

Here's the plan:

  1. We will iterate over all of the Optuna Studies we performed over the last 4 sprints, and pick the best performing model for each of the tasks
  2. We will train our models with the training dataset
    • Remeber that we have not used the training dataset, yet!
    • We have used the hyper_ dataset for all of the hyperparameter tuning.
    • In the cases where cross validation was beneficial, we have split the dataset using 5-fold CV and we have used that subset of data
  3. We will use the test dataset to assess the performance of our models to see how well the do.
    • Remeber that we have not used the training dataset, yet!
  4. Normally, we would then decide if any of the models are good enough to be deployed.
    • This criteria would be defined BEFORE the project starts.
    • However, since this is a learning exercise, we will deploy them all, because the models that we expect to perform poorly will be useful to learn some intermediate app dev skills: (eg. how to use dynamic dispatching of one request and send it to the correct sub model for that specific grade/subgrade).
    • Again. We're only doing this because this is a learning project.
  5. We will then build a flask application that can handle HTTP requests
  6. We will configure out environment with out Google Cloud Credentials
  7. We will deploy the application to GoogleCloud
  8. We will test that it works and that it response as expected.
  9. We will go get a well deserved ice-cream, and call it a day!
    • If you have made it this far, you also deserve a premium ice cream for all of the work you have put in reviewing this project.
    • If you are ever around, reach out and I will gladly go buy you an icecream!
    • Well done!! You are a hero!

In [10]:
def iterate_files(path):
    return [
        os.path.join(root, file) for root, _, files in os.walk(path) for file in files
    ]
In [11]:
def optuna_studies_for_sprint(sprint: int) -> list:
    all_files = iterate_files("optuna_studies")
    return [
        file.replace("optuna_studies/study_", "").replace(".db", "")
        for file in all_files
        if file.startswith(f"optuna_studies/study_sprint{sprint}_")
    ]
In [12]:
from collections import defaultdict

best_model_for_sprint = {}
grade_studies = defaultdict(float)
grade_study_name = defaultdict(str)

for sprint in [1, 2, 3, 4]:
    study_names = optuna_studies_for_sprint(sprint)
    study_scores = {
        study_name: optuna_utils.get_study(study_name).best_value
        for study_name in study_names
    }

    if sprint == 3:
        for name, score in study_scores.items():
            grade = name[-1:]
            if score > grade_studies[grade]:
                grade_studies[grade] = score
                grade_study_name[grade] = name
    elif sprint == 4:
        best_model = min(study_scores, key=study_scores.get)
        best_model_for_sprint[sprint] = best_model
    else:
        best_model = max(study_scores, key=study_scores.get)
        best_model_for_sprint[sprint] = best_model


display(best_model_for_sprint)

display(grade_studies)
display(grade_study_name)

  • 🟡 Sprint 2 to perform relatively well
  • 🔴 Sprint 3 (all models) to perform poorly (and to be discarded from deployment to production due to their poor performance)

In [16]:
def train_model(filename):
    X_train = None
    y_train = None

    start = time()
    if filename == "sprint_1":
        print("using", Sprint.acceptance)
        X_train = dataset_load(Sprint.acceptance, Phase.train, Dataset.X)
        y_train = dataset_load(Sprint.acceptance, Phase.train, Dataset.y)
    elif filename == "sprint_2":
        print("using", Sprint.grade)
        X_train = dataset_load(Sprint.grade, Phase.train, Dataset.X)
        y_train = dataset_load(Sprint.grade, Phase.train, Dataset.y)
    elif filename in [
        "sprint_3_grade_A",
        "sprint_3_grade_B",
        "sprint_3_grade_C",
        "sprint_3_grade_D",
        "sprint_3_grade_E",
        "sprint_3_grade_F",
        "sprint_3_grade_G",
    ]:
        print("using", Sprint.subgrade)
        X_train = dataset_load(Sprint.subgrade, Phase.train, Dataset.X)
        y_train = dataset_load(Sprint.subgrade, Phase.train, Dataset.y)

        grade = filename[-1:]
        X_train["grade"] = y_train.str.get(0)
        X_train = X_train.groupby("grade").get_group(grade).drop(columns="grade")
        y_train = y_train.loc[X_train.index]

    elif filename == "sprint_4":
        print("using", Sprint.interest)
        X_train = dataset_load(Sprint.interest, Phase.train, Dataset.X)
        y_train = dataset_load(Sprint.interest, Phase.train, Dataset.y)
    else:
        raise ValueError(f"invalid filename {filename}")

    print(f"starting {filename}", X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
    n = min(200_000, X_train.shape[0])
    print(f"using {n} rows")
    X, y = pandas_utils.xy_sample(X_train, y_train, n=n)

    model.fit(X, y)
    end = time()
    print(n, end - start)
    joblib.dump(model, f"models/{filename}.model")

In [66]:
def summary_confusion_matrix(sprint: Sprint, model_filename: str, ax=None):
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.gca()
    X = dataset_load(sprint, Phase.test, Dataset.X)
    y = dataset_load(sprint, Phase.test, Dataset.y)

    X_test, expected = pandas_utils.xy_sample(X, y, n=100_000)

    model = joblib.load(f"models/{model_filename}.model")
    predicted = model.predict(X_test)
    cm = yellowbrick.classifier.ConfusionMatrix(
        model, percent=True, is_fitted=True, ax=ax
    )
    cm.score(X_test, expected)
    return ax
In [67]:
def summary_residuals_plot(sprint: Sprint, model_filename: str, ax=None):
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.gca()
    X = dataset_load(sprint, Phase.test, Dataset.X)
    y = dataset_load(sprint, Phase.test, Dataset.y)

    X_test, expected = pandas_utils.xy_sample(X, y, n=100_000)

    model = joblib.load(f"models/{model_filename}.model")
    predicted = model.predict(X_test)
    rp = yellowbrick.regressor.ResidualsPlot(model, percent=True, is_fitted=True, ax=ax)
    rp.score(X_test, expected)
    return ax

Creating the web app¶

This is not the first time we create an app that loads models and uses them to predict.

However, it IS the first time we have models exceeding 700MB that need to be deployed.

Since these cannot be deployed to Google Cloud Engine, they will be stored in a bucket, and fetched at runtime (and cached!) when needed.

Developing this app is not too hard. The only new thing was this:

yes, these values (bucketname) could be parameterized... but some small things were rushed due to deadlines.

Deploying to Google Cloud¶

The last part is the actual deployment to google cloud

Technical Deep dive and lessons learned¶

This section contains "lessons learned" beyond the scope of the project (by trying some extra challenges)

I decided to keep it short and only share the crazier stories.

About highly-concurrenct code, memory management and SIGSEGV (Segmentation Fault)¶

You will notice that during Sprint 2, we only use 14k rows in the code for parallelizing Optuna optimizations.

(actually, that might no longer be the case: I wrote this one crazy night at 4AM and, even though the bug described here was real, I have never again been able to replicate it... so it is possible that in the end I decided to hyper-tune the model using more than 14k)...

Anwyay... back to the story: remember, it's 4AM on a crazy August night:

We have noticed that if the dataset we use for this is above 5MB (not 4.9MB, but 5MB or above), we get our subprocesses killed with SIGSEGV (Segmentation fault) = exit code 11

This was tested with the following row ranges: From 0 to 14k: ✅ From 0 to 14.5k: ✅ From 0 to 15k: ❌ From 14k to 15k: ✅

From 10k to 24k: ✅ From 10k to 24.5k: ✅ From 10k to 25k: ❌

Visualized (each box = 10k rows):

  • 🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛ - ✅
  • 🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛ - ❌
  • ⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛ - ✅
  • ⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛🟨⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛ - ✅
  • ⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛ - ✅
  • ⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨🟨⬛⬛⬛⬛⬛ - ❌
  • and many others that I no longer remember, but they all consistently behaved the same way. It was not actually the number of rows but the size of the memory used.

This drove me to the conclusion that the issue was not "bad data" hiding at row 15001, but that it was the amount of memory.

This was an issue wven when using Manager.list() to handle/wrap objects so each process gets its own individual copy.

After so many rounds of testing, debugging, logging, inspecting and attempting to fix it various workarounds (timing, deep copies of data, avoiding accidental data sharing from different processes), I found no solution that allowed me to use the entire dataset.

Fortunately, it was not necessary to use the entire dataset for tuning. Even just 14k was plenty to provide a farily good f1 score and pretty good performance.

PS thoughts¶

As I reflect on it now, there were other options I could have tried (if I suspected that the issue was sharing data across subprocesses). One of the things I could have tried would be to use a different chunk of the dataset for each of the processes...

I'll list this a "things that I will remember for next project!". It might not result in "using the entire dataset for tuning", because each process will only use a subset.. but, hey! If it works for random forests... why wouldn't it works for Optuna! 🤔

What are segmentation faults¶

If you ever notice that the processes you are spinning up fail to complete and you see this number (-11) when you inspect their return codes, you know you have a problem with the OS killing the processes because they tried to access data that they were not allowed to access.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Segmentation_fault

An exit code of -11 usually indicates a segmentation fault (SIGSEGV) in Linux. A segmentation fault is an error that occurs when a program tries to access memory that it is not allowed to access, such as trying to write to read-only memory or trying to read or write outside the bounds of an array. This can be caused by a variety of issues, such as programming errors, hardware faults, or issues with the operating system or libraries.

To diagnose the issue, you may want to check the logs or output of the subprocesses to see if there are any error messages or stack traces that can provide more information about the cause of the segmentation fault. You can also try running the subprocesses under a debugger, such as gdb, to get more detailed information about the state of the program at the time of the crash.

One of the many attempts to fix it¶

Understanding what was happening¶

One of the hypothesis I had when debugging this was that maybe this was being caused by shared data across processes (instead of copies)

A bit of logging demonstrated that each of the processes was accessing the same memory locations.

The solution involved creating deep copies of the objects.

Trying to fix it using deep copies of the data¶

Process Explorer shows the moment 9 subprocesses are started (the initial spike in CPU for a few seconds that impacts all cores), and then a bunch of squiggly lines as the processes become free and start a new round.

The main concern was that making multiple copies of the data (so each process has its own independent copy) might be too much, but the small bump in memory seems very reasonable and makes this approach possible.

Despite this (one of the attempts at using copies of the data), the solution did not scale beyond 15k rows

Final plot twist¶

Turns out... the very next day, after a healthy reboot, everything started working again...

After spending 3h last night debugging some crazy obscure (yet very consistent) behaviour... after a system reboot, today everything works, even when we cross the 15k threshold!

The process completed successfully:

It could be some flaky thing, or even some of the updates I applied (before rebooting)...

we will never know, but I am happy I got to learn so much about writing highly concurrent code, and that this proves that it was not an issue with the data or (more importantly) with my code.

Remember that it cannot be the data, because that has been already split and cleaned as a once-off task, so the data is the same no matter how many times I reboot the PC.

About Hyperparameter Tuning approaches¶

Optuna seems like a powerful tool, but I often wondered about ways to improve things even more.

The idea of doing a 2-phased approach to hyperparameter tuning crossed my mind a few times.

It seemed reasonable to do a "quick scan" of the search space (fast, with 10% of the data), and follow by doing an "in depth" optimization of the hyperparameters.

Unfortunately, this did not prove to be useful.. The Analysis below shows that, even though the two pass improves over time (the second slow pass is better than the first fast one), they are still far from the better performing approach (a single pass with all of the data).

The time taken on the fast pass was a really good start, but not enough to justify losing 10% to 20% of the performance.

It's pretty clear that the 2-phased approach produces worse results. So in the end, I decided to use 1 slow round instead of 2 fast ones.

About Model Complexity and detecting bugs¶

Something interesting was seeing how the different models for predicting subgrade behaved differently.

Of particular interest is the numerous differences between model for grade B and model for grade C:

  • Remember: The amount of data for grade B and C is very similar and they are both the most common grades, by far.

Despite this, there were numerous differences to highlight:

  • The model for grade C was a lot smaller on disk, but took longer to train (though not a lot)
  • The model for grade B was a lot larger, but was faster to train
    • The size for the model was the expected size if we were to extrapolate when comparing to model A

This might point to interesting patterns in the data that the model might have learned.

PS: Plot twist! At the end I realized that this difference in size was because I had accidentally trained the model to predict the WRONG target variable.. so it was going into super-overfitting territory, and trying to learn all of the crazy edge cases.

After fixing this and retraining, the model was no longer 5.7GB! 😎

Conclusions¶

Executive Summary¶

This project focuses on the loans dataset available from Kaggle.

It provides numerous challenges:

  • A really large dataset (+2GB)
  • A great opportunity to improve data wrangling and cleaning skills. The vast majority of effort was on data cleaning, getting familiar with the data and finding weird patterns and spots to clean.
  • A steep learning curve:
    • The 4 challenges come in increasing difficulty and require more and more refined skills to not get trapped in the mud.
  • Bonus points if you have a PC with limited resources!

Overall, I am happy I got to do it, but what I am really happy about is.. about finishing it! (no doubt you are also happy to be finishing this correction)

On Growth¶

It has been, no doubt, a challenge I won't forget easily, but I'm quite satisfied with the results.

It has been a nightmare to get everything to the level of quality that I wanted. I do not regret having gone into unexplored territory (learning optuna in depth, or how to write (and debug) highly concurrent code in linux AND windows, come to mind), even if it has meant it took me a bit longer to complete it.

I hope you had as much fun reading this I as I did figuring things out! :)

Future improvements¶

  • I heard it's possible to use GPUs for XGBoost - https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/gpu/index.html
    • My laptop has no discrete GPU, but it would be nice to explore in the future on a PC with a GPU and comapre the performance boost that it gives.
